      commentary: `This is among the most direct verses in the entire Gita — four consecutive imperatives. Fix your mind. Be devoted. Worship. Bow. And then the promise: you will come to me.\n\nMan-manā bhava — "have your mind on me." Not occasionally. Not as a category among many. The mind naturally follows what it cares most deeply about. Most people's minds follow approval, security, pleasure, success — cycling endlessly between craving and fear. Krishna is asking for a reorientation of what the mind moves toward. When the mind has found its deepest object, the restlessness begins to settle.\n\nMat-parāyaṇaḥ — "with me as the supreme goal." Parāyaṇa means ultimate refuge, final resting place. This is not about renouncing other goals. It is about establishing a hierarchy. When you know what the deepest goal is, every smaller goal finds its right place. The career, the relationship, the health — none of these disappear. But they are held differently. They are not the last word.\n\nThe verse appears near-identical to 18.65. That repetition is significant. Of everything Krishna says across 700 verses, he repeats this one. It is the instruction he most wants to land. Fix your mind on me. Everything else follows.`,
